óŔXarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2020-06-30-nushell_0_16_0.mdŔ@04df0efc659bca709beea45e88df1bfdd30b8a1805d3c9deb8f7e005c6ca1b4dĶtitle: Nushell 0.16.0ĎĻCustom prompts (sophiajt)ŕYou can now run a pipeline which returns a string, or list of strings, that is used to create a custom prompt. To do so, set the pipeline you want to use in the config for the 
``prompt``
 setting.
A simple example:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt "echo '> '"]

```
We've also added a new 
``ansi``
 command to let you change the color. Let's use it to change the prompt to blue:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt "echo $(ansi blue) '> '"]

```
You can make the prompt even fancier. For example, this prompt prints the current directory, git branch, and current date and time:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt 'echo [ $(ansi green) $(pwd) $(ansi reset) $(do -i {git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD } | trim | echo [ "(" $(ansi blue) $it $(ansi reset) ")" ] | str join) $(char newline) $(ansi cyan) $(date --format "%d/%m/%Y %H:%M:%S").formatted $(ansi reset) "> " ]']

```
image of full prompt
Example of full prompt
Or update your prompt to show an abbreviated path:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt 'echo [ $(ansi green) $(pwd | split row "/" | first $(pwd | split row "/" | count | = $it - 1 ) | each { str substring "0,1" | format "{$it}/" } | append $(pwd | split row "/" | last ) | str join) $(do -i { git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD | trim | echo $(ansi reset) "(" $(ansi blue) $it $(ansi reset) ")" | str join }) $(ansi reset) "> "]']

```
(note: the above assumes Unix-based systems, so on Windows use "
" as the path separator))
image of abbreviated prompt
Example of abbreviated prompt
íźźŕSTitle: title: Nushell 0.16.0
Path: Custom prompts (sophiajt)
Content:
You can now run a pipeline which returns a string, or list of strings, that is used to create a custom prompt. To do so, set the pipeline you want to use in the config for the 
``prompt``
 setting.
A simple example:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt "echo '> '"]

```
We've also added a new 
``ansi``
 command to let you change the color. Let's use it to change the prompt to blue:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt "echo $(ansi blue) '> '"]

```
You can make the prompt even fancier. For example, this prompt prints the current directory, git branch, and current date and time:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt 'echo [ $(ansi green) $(pwd) $(ansi reset) $(do -i {git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD } | trim | echo [ "(" $(ansi blue) $it $(ansi reset) ")" ] | str join) $(char newline) $(ansi cyan) $(date --format "%d/%m/%Y %H:%M:%S").formatted $(ansi reset) "> " ]']

```
image of full prompt
Example of full prompt
Or update your prompt to show an abbreviated path:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> config --set [prompt 'echo [ $(ansi green) $(pwd | split row "/" | first $(pwd | split row "/" | count | = $it - 1 ) | each { str substring "0,1" | format "{$it}/" } | append $(pwd | split row "/" | last ) | str join) $(do -i { git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD | trim | echo $(ansi reset) "(" $(ansi blue) $it $(ansi reset) ")" | str join }) $(ansi reset) "> "]']

```
(note: the above assumes Unix-based systems, so on Windows use "
" as the path separator))
image of abbreviated prompt
Example of abbreviated prompt
